egory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/G04127X/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The proposed research aims to contribute directly to the policy debate concerned with the financing of Higher Education&amp;nbsp;- in particular: the contributions that taxpayer, parents and students make towards its costs, the extent to which these contributions should be loans or grants, and how such payments might be designed. For example, one could contrast financing systems based on mortgage loans with one based on income contingent loans. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The aim is to contribute to this area of research in a number of important ways by considering: grants versus loans versus graduate tax, merit based support versus universal support, means tested versus not, and tax deductibility versus not. &lt;/p>

&lt;p>The work will involve theory, estimation and policy option simulation. It will incorporate how student finance interacts with the tax system and so lead to more complex and realistic estimates of the returns to higher education. Estimation will be more flexible than the previous literature in an important way&amp;nbsp;- the work will relax the common restriction that age-earnings profiles are assumed to be parallel across education levels. Finally, the empirical research will consider the role of family background so that policies that incorporate means testing against parental income can be considered.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2011-09-30</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2009-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>132034</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>50E07E31-6A87-4791-9711-7F5633892050</gtr:id><gtr:title>An Evaluation of Multiple Overlapping Policies in a Multi-Level Framework: The Case of Secondary Education Policies in the UK</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Education Economics</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/ad4612202bc5f92a97d4fd783e4446b2"><gtr:id>ad4612202bc5f92a97d4fd783e4446b2</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Bradley S</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2012-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>545d7bc